'''João Maria''' was the name given to three lay monks who were in turn active in southern Brazil during the second half of the 19th century and early 20th century, although two originally had other names and the third was only called João Maria after his death. They were all ascetic wanderers and preachers who healed with herbs. The third led a peasant revolt in 1912. Their followers think they were the same person in different incarnations, a saint. The [[Monge State Park]]{{efn|The [[Monge State Park]] is named after the first monk ({{lang-pt|Monge João Maria}}).{{sfn|Lapa: Parque Estadual do Monge ... Paraná Turismo}} }} maintains a cave where the first monk once lived, visited by thousands of pilgrims annually.

==João Maria D’Agostini==
[[File:O monge João Maria em 1861.jpg|thumb|João Maria D’Agostini in 1861]]
{{main|João Maria D’Agostini}}
The first João Maria was born in [[Piemont]], Italy.{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=94}}
As a young man he entered the seminary in Rome, but left before being ordained priest.
He wandered in Europe, then came to South America where he travelled in Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and finally Brazil.
There are records from 1844 of João Maria going from [[Pará]] to [[Rio de Janeiro]], where he became famous as a healer and counselor.
He moved to [[Sorocaba]] and continued to practice medicine and give advice.{{sfn|Olhos d'água do monge João Maria ... Prudentópolis}}

João Maria left the city of [[São Paulo]] and disappeared for a while before showing up in [[Rio Grande do Sul]].{{sfn|Olhos d'água do monge João Maria ... Prudentópolis}}
Thousands of people came to him at Cerro Campestre, in [[Santa Maria, Rio Grande do Sul]], drawn by word of the miraculous power of his waters.
The authorities of Rio Grande do Sul analyzed the water and found it was potable but no different from any other water.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1911}}
He then continued through Santa Catarina and [[Paraná (state)|Paraná]], where he lived in a cave near [[Lapa, Paraná|Lapa]] in 1847.
There he performed marriages, baptisms, healings and gave blessings to the local people.{{sfn|Olhos d'água do monge João Maria ... Prudentópolis}}
João Maria was not a revolutionary, but tried to improve the condition of the peasants.{{sfn|Feldman|Hata|1989|p=257}}
He organized processions, built chapels, blessed cattle and baptized children.
He cared for the sick, and his herbal teas became famous.{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=94}}

In 1848 João Maria was deported to Santa Catarina, then to Rio de Janeiro, where he was lost from sight for a while.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1911}}
He reappeared in [[Buenos Aires]] in 1853 and walked through Bolivia and all of south and central America until 1861, arriving in [[New Mexico]] in the United States in 1862, where he lived in the mountains.
He was assassinated there on 17 April 1869 at the age of 69.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1911}}
His tomb may be seen in New Mexico.{{sfn|Olhos d'água do monge João Maria ... Prudentópolis}}

==João Maria de Jesus==
[[File:Monge João Maria d. 1869.jpg|thumb|João Maria de Jesus in 1898]]
{{main|João Maria de Jesus}}
In 1890 João Maria de Jesus began to travel in southern Brazil.
His appearance, with a long white beard, and way of life were similar to Agostini.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1911}}
João Maria de Jesus was famous as a healer, and his medicine was thought to be miraculous.
It was said he could cure a person simply by praying for their health and prescribing a tea from a common herb called "monk's broom".{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1912}}
He was quoted as saying , "He who does not know how to read the book of nature is illiterate in God's eyes."{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=94}}
His devotees thought that all objects or places that he touched became sacred, and would provide the hermit's blessings after he had disappeared.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1912}}

During the [[Federalist Riograndense Revolution|Federalist Revolution]] of 1893–95 he attended wounded rebels.{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=94}}
His teachings were prophetic and apocalyptic.
He said God would punish mankind with plagues of insects and bloody wars.
He thought the  [[First Brazilian Republic]] of 1889 was the work of the devil, and defended restoration of the monarchy as the "order of God".
He may have died in 1908 in hospital in [[Ponta Grossa]], Paraná, or may be buried in [[Lagoa Vermelha]], Rio Grande do Sul, but his devotees think he is still living in the Morro Taió, a hill in Santa Catarina.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1912}}

[[File:José Maria Monge do Contestado.jpg|thumb|José Maria de Santo Agostinho]]

==José Maria de Santo Agostinho==
{{main|José Maria de Santo Agostinho}}
[[José Maria de Santo Agostinho]] was formerly the soldier Miguel Lucena de Boaventura.
He settled in Taquaraçu, Santa Catarina, where he gained a reputation for healing powers.
He established a "people's pharmacy" where he would provide herbs, seeds and roots as well as prayers.{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=93}}
José Maria claimed to be the first João Maria's brother.{{sfn|Feldman|Hata|1989|p=257}}
He was the religious leader of the rebels during the "[[Contestado War]]" of 1912–16, in which small farmers and settlers in [[Paraná (state)|Paraná]] and Santa Catarina who had been expelled from their lands fought against the large capitalist landowners and companies.{{sfn|Cueto|Palmer|2014|p=94}}
He organized the dispossessed peasants and sharecroppers from his base at the Fazenda do Irani.{{sfn|Feldman|Hata|1989|p=257}}

The state government's security regiment marched to Taquaruçu to disperse his followers.
In a clash on 22 October 1912 the troops were defeated, but José Maria, who was leading the rebels, was killed.
In their religious excitement the rebels sanctified José Maria and began to call him São João Maria, thinking he would return in a few months with an enchanted army commanded by Saint Sebastian.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1913}}

==Legacy==
The people of the region began to conflate José Maria and the João Marias, uniting them as one person.
A socio-religious movement led by André Ferreira França began in [[Soledade]], Rio Grande do Sul, in 1935.
The group was persecuted and André França decided to withdraw, but was shot in a clash with the city's military brigade.{{sfn|Silva|Kunrath|2015|p=1913}}

There is a large literature about the monks called João Maria, but the devout population have little interest in their historicity and are much more concerned with the sacred characteristics attributed to them.{{sfn|Alves|2010|p=36}}
There are people today who think that João Maria, now more than 200 years old, still wanders in the region and works his miracles.
There are many places in the center and east of [[Paraná (state)|Paraná]] and Santa Catarina, the south of [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo]] and the north of [[Rio Grande do Sul]], where a small altar or cross marks a place where one of the "João Marias" would have passed.{{sfn|Kubaski|2012}}

The various wanderers recognized as the monk or prophet João Maria  all have strong similarities.
They are pilgrims, without home or family. They have withdrawn from the pleasures of the world to do penance by serving God.
They preach the [[Apocalypse]], when God will punish all sinners.
They have the miraculous power of healing, and they are immortal.{{sfn|Welter |2007|p=47}}

The [[Monge State Park]] was created in [[Lapa, Paraná|Lapa]] in 1960.
The main attraction is the monk's cave, a place of religious pilgrimage for thousands of faithful. 
It includes a source of water that it considered to be miraculous.{{sfn|Lapa: Parque Estadual do Monge ... Paraná Turismo}}
In 2015 Paraná Turismo was considering definition of a tourist circuit to visit the ''olhos d'água'' in places where the monk was present.
As of December 2015 the secretariat of tourism had identified 38 municipalities where the monk was present.{{sfn|Olhos d'água do monge João Maria ... Prudentópolis}}

