'''Thomas Fulljames''' (1808-1874) was the [[county surveyor]] for [[Gloucestershire]] and a leading architect and civil engineer in that county in the first half of the nineteenth century.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/glos/vol4/pp311-317#h3-0010 St. Luke, High Orchard], ''British History Online''. Retrieved 26 August 2017.</ref>
== Life == He studied surveying with his uncle Thomas Fulljames (died 1847) and architecture with [[Thomas Rickman]].<ref>David Verey and Alan Brooks. [https://books.google.com/books?id=m9W2XH11-9EC&lpg=PA105&ots=zX4z7U_gse&dq=Thomas%20Fulljames&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false Gloucestershire: The Vale and the Forest of Dean]. New Haven, Ct.: Yale University Press, 1976.</ref> Among his designs was the [[Church of St Luke, Gloucester|Church of St Luke]], High Orchard, Gloucester, which opened in 1841<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4mI3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA644 "Domestic Occurrences"], ''The Gentleman's Magazine'', 1841, p. 644.</ref> and was demolished in 1934.
